english:
  title: Record of the Stone Rhinoceros Pavilion
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The county of Gwangju is enclosed by great mountains on three sides—east, south, and west—while only the north opens onto distant plains. Two streams flow from the valleys of the southern mountains, their sources lying far away. When these waters merge, their combined force grows formidable, as any man can see. Each summer when the rains come in torrents, the savage currents rush down with terrible power, destroying homes and tearing away fields. The suffering of the people is grievous. How could those who govern not give this grave matter their deepest concern?

    Below the southern mountains stood the Water-Dividing Temple, where the ancients once sought to break the water's fury. Yet their efforts proved insufficient. So where the two streams clashed and collided, men raised walls of stone to redirect the waters westward and northward. Since the land slopes toward the north, the water follows nature's course, and the people's suffering ceased.

    Upon the old riverbed, they built a pavilion at the very meeting point of the streams. The waters were channeled to flow on both sides, encircling the pavilion on all four sides like the walls of jade. Before and behind the pavilion, earth was heaped into small islands where flowering trees were planted. Floating bridges were laid for passage. Seated within, one whistles and composes poems as if drifting on a raft upon the sea, watching islands rise and disappear through mist and waves—truly, a place of perfect joy.

    When the Huihu official Seuol Cheon-yong traveled south, he visited this pavilion. Upon his return to the capital, he sent word through Prefect Kim, requesting a name and record for the place.

    I replied: "Yu the Great controlled the waters, as recorded in the Yu Gong. His method was simply to follow the water's nature and guide it accordingly. The Qin appointed Li Bing to govern Shu, and Li Bing carved a stone rhinoceros to suppress water disasters. Later, when Li Dao-yuan compiled the Water Classic, that stone rhinoceros was no longer the original work of Li Bing, yet those who spoke of water control thereafter always invoked his name. By this we may perceive how Li Bing's wisdom endures. Thus the poet Du Fu composed verse:

    'If the primal breath maintains its harmony,
    Waves and floods will naturally recede.
    Oh, to find a mighty hero to grasp heaven's rope,
    And restore order where the stone rhinoceros once roamed!'

    He speaks of harmonizing the primal breath and ordering earth and water—the work of the Two Sages and Three Kings. Yet the wisdom of those ancient rulers, though it remains inherent in later generations, is something men forever seek anew through cunning and extraordinary means.

    Yet Confucius once said: 'Even in small things, there is much to observe.' That stone suppresses water is known even to the most simple. The rhinoceros form holds its own logic. The Book of Master Baopuo records: 'Carve a rhinoceros as a fish to swallow water, and the waters part three feet.' Thus the rhinoceros, being that creature which repels water, possesses great efficacy. Stone is the bone of mountains; the rhinoceros resists water. Water, knowing this, must give way. So guided downward without hesitation, it flows through open lands, streaming on until it reaches the sea—what harm can it then cause? What unease can afflict the townspeople?

    In recording this pavilion, no blame attends the work. Thus we name it the Stone Rhinoceros Pavilion, taking Du Fu's verse as foundation and the Book of Master Baopuo as witness. By the principles of the Spring and Autumn Annals, we make clear that this pavilion was built to prevent water disaster and secure the people's dwelling—not merely for idle viewing. Those who ascend this pavilion and contemplate its name and meaning will surely feel reverence for Prefect Kim.

    The prefect's name is Sang. He has served as keeper of records in the prefectural office and as censor, and is known throughout his administration for his honesty and able governance.
  footnotes:
    - Li Bing (李冰) was a legendary hydraulic engineer of the Warring States period who served the state of Qin. The stone rhinoceros became a famous symbol of water control in Chinese history.
    - Du Fu (杜甫), known as Du Gongbu (杜工部), was one of China's greatest poets of the Tang Dynasty.
    - The 'Two Sages' (二帝) refers to the legendary sage-kings Yao and Shun; the 'Three Kings' (三王) refers to Yu the Great, Tang the Sage, and King Wen.
    - The Book of Master Baopuo (抱朴子) is a Daoist philosophical text attributed to Ge Hong (葛洪) from the Eastern Jin period.
    - The reference to 'Spring and Autumn Annals' invokes the historical and moral judgment recorded in that classic text.
